    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="192"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d192">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CC2" type="from"
                            >Churchill</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_RFD1" type="to"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d192fn1">Sent by the American Embassy, London, presumably
                        via military channels. For further excerpts from this telegram, see <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_68">p. 68</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-11-06">6 November
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Nr. 493 <gloss target="#t_FormerNavalPerson1">Former Naval Person</gloss> to
                    President personal and most secret.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Para 3. Please also refer to your number 407.<note n="2" xml:id="d192fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_151">p. 151</ref>.</note>
                    Since I telegraphed thanking you for this<note n="3" xml:id="d192fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName>’s “Thank you” telegram was
                        No. 492, November 5, 1943, to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt
                            (Roosevelt</persName> Papers).</note> the British Chiefs of Staff have
                    examined the proviso in the last part of this telegram. They do not think that
                    the Commanders should be responsible for allotting the forces for <gloss
                        target="#t_Overlord1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Overlord</hi>
                    </gloss>, operations in Italy and the Eastern Mediterranean, but that this
                    should remain as hitherto the duty of the Combined Chiefs of Staff who would
                    naturally have before them the opinion of the “Commanders responsible”. They
                    would therefore like to leave out the words “Commanders responsible” and insert
                    “The Combined Chiefs of Staff”. Will you very kindly think over this. I imagine
                    we all mean the same thing.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
        </body>
